UPI fraud is one of the most common types of cybercrime today, especially in countries like India where digital payments are widely used. In simple terms, it happens when someone tricks a person into sending money through apps like Google Pay, PhonePe, or Paytm.
This kind of fraud usually starts with a phone call, message, or even a chat on social media. The scammer pretends to be someone trustworthy, like a bank employee, customer care executive, or even a buyer interested in purchasing something online. First, they try to gain the victim’s trust by speaking politely and sounding genuine. Then, they create a sense of urgency, saying things like “your account will be blocked” or “you need to verify your details.” After that, they send a payment request or QR code and tell the victim to approve it to receive money. Many people don’t realize that entering their UPI PIN actually sends money instead of receiving it.
Students, elderly people, and those who are not very familiar with digital payments are often targeted. The impact can be serious—people can lose their savings within minutes. It also causes stress and fear, making people lose confidence in online transactions.
This shows how important it is to stay aware. A simple rule to remember is: you never need to enter your UPI PIN to receive money.
